anese Monetary Policy -- t14 Testing for the Fundamental Determinants of the Long- Run Real Exchange Rate: The Case of Taiwan -- t15 Hong Kong's Currency Board and Changing Monetary Regimes -- tContributors -- tAuthor Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe exchange rate is a crucial variable linking a nation's domestic economy to the international market. Thus choice of an exchange rate regime is a central component in the economic policy of developing countries and a key factor affecting economic growth. Historically, most developing nations have employed strict exchange rate controls and heavy protection of domestic industry-policies now thought to be at odds with sustainable and desirable rates of economic growth. By contrast, many East Asian nations maintained exchange rate regimes designed to achieve an attractive climate for exports and an "outer-oriented" development strategy. The result has been rapid and consistent economic growth over the past few decades. Changes in Exchange Rates in Rapidly Developing Countries explores the impact of such diverse exchange control regimes in both historical and regional contexts, focusing particular attention on East Asia. This comprehensive, carefully researched volume will surely become a standard reference for scholars and policymakers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aForeign exchange ratesxCongressesxDeveloping countries. 0aForeign exchange ratesxCongressesxEast Asia. 0aForeign exchange rateszDeveloping countriesvCongresses. 0aForeign exchange rateszEast AsiavCongresses. 0aForeign exchangexCongressesxGovernment policyxDeveloping countries. 0aForeign exchangexCongressesxGovernment policyxEast Asia. 0aForeign exchangexGovernment policyzDeveloping